  "footnotes": [
    "Kingdom of Mapungubwe (c.1075–1220): Located at the confluence of the Limpopo and Shashe rivers (modern Zimbabwe-South Africa-Botswana border), Mapungubwe was the first class-stratified society in southern Africa; its rulers were buried on a hilltop separate from commoners with golden artefacts including the famous golden rhinoceros; abandoned c.1290 possibly due to climate change.",
    "Kingdom of Great Zimbabwe (c.1220–1450): The largest medieval stone structure in sub-Saharan Africa, Great Zimbabwe at its peak housed 10,000–18,000 people; its rulers controlled the gold trade between the interior plateau and the Swahili coast ports; the site gives modern Zimbabwe its name; decline was likely caused by overgrazing, deforestation, and shifting trade routes.",
    "Mutapa Empire (c.1430–1760): Founded by Nyatsimba Mutota after the fall of Great Zimbabwe; controlled gold and ivory trade; Portuguese traders and missionaries penetrated the empire from the coast, eventually making it a vassal state (1629); it survived in diminished form until Rozvi expansion displaced it.",
    "Rozvi Empire / Changamire dynasty (c.1660–1830s): The Rozvi expelled the Portuguese from the Zimbabwe Plateau in 1693; their capital Khami and other stone-walled sites continued the Great Zimbabwe building tradition; the empire was destroyed by Ngoni (Nguni) raiding groups displaced by the Mfecane.",
    "Mfecane (c.1815–1840): A period of widespread chaos and warfare in southern Africa triggered by the rise of the Zulu Kingdom under Shaka; mass migrations created new states as far north as Tanzania; the Ndebele (Matabele) under Mzilikazi fled Shaka and settled in the Zimbabwe Plateau; the Sotho under Moshoeshoe founded Lesotho; population dislocations affected millions.",
    "Zulu Kingdom (1816–1879): Shaka kaSenzangakhona revolutionized Zulu military tactics (the 'bull horn' formation, the short stabbing spear); the kingdom expanded rapidly and absorbed neighboring chiefdoms; after Shaka's assassination (1828), it continued under Dingane, Mpande, and Cetshwayo; the Anglo-Zulu War (1879) ended with British victory after the shock defeat at Isandlwana.",
    "Anglo-Boer Wars (1880–1881, 1899–1902): The First Boer War ended in Boer victory at Majuba Hill; the Second Boer War (South African War) was the largest British campaign since the Napoleonic Wars; Britain used concentration camps in which ~26,000 Boer civilians and ~14,000–20,000 Black Africans died; the Boer republics were absorbed into the British Empire.",
    "Union of South Africa (1910–1961): Created by the South Africa Act 1909 uniting Cape, Natal, Transvaal, and OFS; a self-governing dominion within the British Empire; the 1913 Natives Land Act restricted Black land ownership to 7% of the country; the National Party victory in 1948 institutionalized apartheid.",
    "Apartheid era (1948–1994): The system of institutionalized racial segregation classified the population into White, Coloured, Indian, and Black groups; the Sharpeville Massacre (1960) and Soweto Uprising (1976) became international symbols of resistance; Nelson Mandela was imprisoned 1964–1990; F.W. de Klerk unbanned the ANC (1990), leading to negotiations and the first fully democratic election in April 1994.",
    "Portuguese Mozambique (1505–1975): Portugal established Sofala (1505) and Mozambique Island as bases for the Indian Ocean trade; the colony was chronically underdeveloped; after the Carnation Revolution in Lisbon (1974), FRELIMO took power; the subsequent civil war with RENAMO (backed by apartheid South Africa and Rhodesia) caused over one million deaths."
  ]
}
